Passive Voice
The primary function of the passive voice is to suppress agency, meaning it is used when the speaker intentionally removes focus from the doer (agent) of an action and places it on what was done. In natural language, the subject position is the "center of attraction," so moving an object to the subject position shifts the focus there.
•	Structure: Passive morphology follows the formula tense + be + en + V3.
•	Transitivity: Only transitive verbs (verbs that take objects) can be passivized because the past participle itself does not take an object.
•	Examples: 
o	"The house was built in 1975" (focus on the house, not the builder).
o	"Classes were suspended" (the principal, the doer, is relegated to an optional adjunct: "by the principal").
Participial Constructions
Participles are derived from verbs but function as modifiers (adjectives) or nouns (gerunds) rather than the main verb of a sentence. They do not host information about time; tense is instead hosted on the main verb of the predicate.
•	Present Participle (V + -ing): Used as an adjective (modifier) or a gerund (noun). 
o	Example: "Running nose" (adjective).
o	Example: "Swimming is fun" (gerund/noun).
•	Past Participle (V + -ed/V3): Often used to modify nouns or form passive/perfective aspects. 
o	Example: "Baked potatoes" or "Roasted chicken".
o	Example: "Raju was wearing a torn shirt".
Negative Sensitive Elements
Certain words in English, known as Negative Polarity Items (NPIs), are contingent upon a negative marker or an interrogative context to be grammatical. When a sentence is negated, the tense must separate from the verb, with the negation appearing between them.
•	Key Elements: Terms like anybody, anyone, anything, any, and phrases like "a penny" or "at all".
•	Examples: 
o	"John did not like anything" (You cannot say "John liked anything").
o	"Sarita did not give a penny" (interpreted as "nothing").
o	"Did you meet with anyone?" (Interrogative context allowing the sensitive element).
Reported Speech
Reported speech involves embedding one sentence within another to report what a previous speaker said. It consists of a reporting clause (independent) and a reported clause (embedded).
•	Structural Shifts: Reports usually require shifting personal pronouns (e.g., "I" to "he/she") and tense (typically shifting to the past because the report occurs later).
•	Examples: 
o	Direct: Raman said, "I will join you."
o	Reported: "Raman said that he would join us for the meeting".
o	"The teacher asked if children would visit the park" (using 'if' for curiosity/questions).
Conditionals
Conditionals are complex sentences containing a subordinate (if-clause) and a main clause. The subordinate clause determines the validity of the main clause.
•	Zero Conditional: Used for general truths or natural laws (Simple Present in both clauses). 
o	Example: "The clay becomes sticky if you add water to it".
•	First Conditional: Real future possibilities. 
o	Example: "If the price of orange rises, demand will fall".
•	Second Conditional: Unreal or hypothetical situations. 
o	Example: "If I had a lot of money, I would buy an airplane".
•	Third Conditional: Imagining a change in the past leading to a different past result. 
o	Example: "If I had prepared well, I would have scored good marks".
•	Mixed Conditionals: Linking a past change to a present result. 
o	Example: "If I had not won the lottery, I would not be on a world tour".
Quantifiers
Quantifiers are a sub-group of determiners that specify quantity.
•	Countable vs. Uncountable: Some work only with countable nouns (many, few, several), while others work with uncountable nouns (much, little).
•	Positive vs. Negative Reading: There is a crucial distinction between "a few/a little" (some/positive) and "few/little" (not many/not much/negative reading).
•	Affirmative vs. Negative: "Some" is primarily for affirmative sentences, while "any" is used in negative or interrogative contexts.
•	Examples: 
o	"I have some money" (affirmative).
o	"I do not have any money" (negative).
o	"A little knowledge is a dangerous thing".

